  "author": "chenyj796",
  "body": "# Summary of the new feature/enhancement\r\n\r\nI use xshell and always set the background to white.\r\nWhen I start pwsh on Linux, the command forecolor is yellow which is very illegible.\r\nHow can I disable the color setting of pwsh?\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18184515/68665754-93fb6b00-057d-11ea-85a9-d0852a3fc8f5.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n# Proposed technical implementation details (optional)\r\n\r\n<!-- \r\nA clear and concise description of what you want to happen.\r\nConsider providing an example PowerShell experience with expected result.\r\n-->\r\n",
  "closed_at": "2019-11-13T00:52:39Z",
  "comments": [
    {
      "author": "iSazonov",
      "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
      "body": "You could temporary set colors with `$host.ui.RawUI`",
      "created_at": "2019-11-12T12:32:41Z",
      "updated_at": "2019-11-12T12:32:41Z"
    },
    {
      "author": "vexx32",
      "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
      "body": "Either that or `Set-PSReadLineOption` can set the color values used; you can recolor them to something more readable for you or just set any annoying colors back to grey/black. \r\n\r\nYou can put lines in your `$profile` script to set these values semi-persistently.",
      "created_at": "2019-11-12T13:25:13Z",
      "updated_at": "2019-11-12T13:25:13Z"
    },
    {
      "author": "lzybkr",
      "author_association": "MEMBER",
      "body": "Ideally a light background can be detected automatically and colors adjusted automatically. See https://github.com/PowerShell/PSReadLine/issues/464 for more info.",
      "created_at": "2019-11-12T22:01:38Z",
      "updated_at": "2019-11-12T22:01:38Z"
    },
    {
      "author": "chenyj796",
      "author_association": "NONE",
      "body": "@vexx32 Thanks.\r\n\r\nThe Set-PSReadLineOption works.\r\n",
      "created_at": "2019-11-13T00:52:38Z",
      "updated_at": "2019-11-13T00:52:38Z"
    },
